7007	Raub	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/thumb/img/iOsdUvqKguJoFq_rQXIQ2XjJ6y8=/fit-in/200x150/pic202602.jpg	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/original/img/ycFL-EYyApY6vQBrmiFJXgdF-Oo=/0x0/pic202602.jpg	Raub is a card game that is widely played amongst Croatians in the United States but it's origins aren't known. The game is played with a "Bavarian" card deck used also in Schafkopf or Preference.  Alternatively, you could use a standard card deck with just the 7,8,9,10,J,Q,K, and Ace of each suit.\n\nThe dealer deals four cards to each player, and turns up one trump card.  The dealer may declare "Raub" before looking at his hand if he wants to take a gamble with the  nice trump card he turned up in attempting to take two tricks.  If it is a 7, the dealer may declare a "shtih" and take a gamble that he will get one trick.  Otherwise, starting with the player on the dealer's right, players declare if they are going to try to play on the trump suit for two or more tricks.  Each player in succession can either play and attempt to get one suit, or drop out completely. Each player discards 1-4 cards and the dealer gives each new cards.\n\nPlayers all start at 21 points, and go down one point for each trick taken.  Failing to win the two trumps when leading will make the player go up 4 points, and failing to take any tricks when following will make the player go up two points.  Hands that aren't played after dealt lead to a "refa" where the scoring of the next hand is doubled.\n\nFinally, when one player is below 10 points, a dealer may declare a "muss" where all players must play.  This is an attempt to cause a player to go up that is in the lead.  This can lead to a player coming close to winning, then another, then another until someone finally hits zero!\n\n	45	45	45	0	4	4	4	(Uncredited)	(Public Domain)
7008	Preference	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/thumb/img/4yHwSX5Su7X0XQe-1kYXpjgnceo=/fit-in/200x150/pic100613.jpg	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/original/img/G33ssWF3MhtLRK9aSYYhtUZBjfQ=/0x0/pic100613.jpg	Preference is a standard deck playing card game played throughout central Europe and Russia using a 32 card "Bavarian" deck like the one used in Schafkopf.  The major varieties of Preference are Croatian, Austrian, and Russian and there are variations of each as well.  Generally a three player game, a fourth player can play by having the dealer of each hand sit out for the round.  Following is a brief description of the Croatian version of the game, and below are links to rule sets for the Croatian, Austrian, and Russian versions.\n\nEach of the suits has a predetermined value:\nLeaves = 2\nBells = 3\nHearts = 4\nAcorns = 5\n\nThe dealer deals out all 32 cards - 10 to each player and 2 to the "talon" (crib).  Each player in turn bids one of the suits for trump, or can bid the value 6 game where the declarer(bid winner) can attempt to take no tricks and the other two must try to force him to do so, or the 7 game where there is no trump suit. The highest bid becomes the declarer, takes the two cards from the "talon" and discards two, and then must take 6 tricks to succeed in the game he bid for or a higher one.  The opposing players have the option to play in which they must get two tricks to succeed.  If only one player is opposing, he may request the aid of the other non-declaring player in an attempt to make the declarer fail in his bid, but takes all the bonuses or penalties for doing so.  Non bid hands means a double scoring round in the next hand, and "kontra" may be offered to double the stakes of a hand a player is confident in making the declarer fail (and can be "rekontra" and "sukontra" or doubled and doubled again and again!).\n\nThe players start out with a set number of points (usually 100 each) and the game goes until the total of all three players equals zero.  Tricks taken when opposing a contract score some points for the player and against those players in the final tally.  \n\n\n	120	120	120	1802	3	4	3	(Uncredited)	(Public Domain)
